---
import BaseLayout from '~/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import TrustNav from '~/components/TrustNav.astro';
import ReviewMethodologyFooter from '~/components/ReviewMethodologyFooter.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Advertising Disclosure — Kefiw"
  description="How Kefiw uses advertising, how ads relate to editorial work, and what ad personalization controls are available."
  canonical="/advertising-disclosure/"
  keywords={['advertising disclosure', 'kefiw ads', 'ad disclosure']}
>
  <article class="container-narrow py-10 prose-tool">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Advertising Disclosure</h1>
    <p class="lead text-lg text-slate-700">
      Kefiw is free because it shows advertising. Ads do not decide calculator formulas, rankings, examples, review labels, or methodology pages.
    </p>

    <TrustNav current="/advertising-disclosure/" />

    <h2>How advertising appears</h2>
    <p>
      Ads may appear in header, footer, inline, or sticky placements. The site separates ad containers from tool output so users can still inspect the formula, assumptions, and result.
    </p>

    <h2>Editorial separation</h2>
    <p>
      A calculator or guide may cover commercial topics, but the output logic should remain deterministic and auditable. Sponsored claims, hidden lead-gen routing, and paid ranking are not part of the current Kefiw model.
    </p>

    <h2>Privacy controls</h2>
    <p>
      Use the bottom-right menu to choose personalized or contextual-only ads where regional rules allow that choice.
    </p>

    <h2>Current approval status</h2>
    <p>
      While Kefiw is preparing for publisher-network review, ad code and visible ad placements may be disabled. The disclosure page stays published so visitors and reviewers can see how monetization is intended to work before ads return.
    </p>
    <p>
      If advertising is re-enabled later, the same editorial separation still applies: ads may support the free site, but they should not change a calculator result, hide the assumptions behind a guide, or turn a page into a paid ranking.
    </p>

    <ReviewMethodologyFooter
      reviewerLinks={[
        { label: 'engineering', href: '/engineering-review/' },
        { label: 'scientific reviewer', href: '/scientific-review/' },
      ]}
    />
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
